Sometimes when I’m struggling with a painting I have to take a step back, shift my perspective and find a new composition. That can mean turning a painting upside down, and sometimes it can mean cutting it up, getting the parts out of it that I like and finding new ways to make something work, and spending less time obsessing on the parts that don’t. Tryna apply this to life right now too cuz it’s been a difficult week. Hope you’re all doing ok out there. ❤️

Sound up for some ASMR if you’re into that kinda thing 📢

“Rarámuri, Four”, Mixed Media on Paint Chip, 4 x 7 1/2” 🔴SOLD

This painting is a part of a series of four, shown at #zonamaco with @hashimotocontemporary 

I recently learned about the fabled Rarámuri runners, with their beautiful traditions, philosophy and fabulous ‘fits. And yes I learned about them from “Limitless with Chris Hemsworth” and yes I watched the entire series in one sitting. It wasn’t lost on me that I was watching a series about the potential of the human body while laying on the couch all day. So I figured painting the Rarámuri was a start, and maybe even someday I’ll do the ice water plunge and maybe I’ll paint about that too. 🥶

New work for “Locals Only” group show curated by @william_wray. Opening Saturday, May 20 at @baldwinavenuegallery in Sierra Madre, CA. Hope to see you there!

“Wildfire Season”, 2023
30 x 24”
Mixed Media on Canvas

In honor of AAPI Heritage month, I wanted to share some work by some phenomenal Asians that inspire me.

I’m so happy to post about Seonna Hong.

 Seonna is a Korean American and was born and raised in Southern California.  Her works have graced gallery walls all over the world, she was even chosen as the first American artist to have a solo show in Takashi Murakami’s gallery Kai Kai Ki Ki. Needless to say her work is incredible and if you’re lucky enough to see her work in person, you’d agree that her talent is beyond words!  Seonna is also an incredible mom to the coolest and kindest young woman, Tigerlily ❤️ I’m so lucky to  have Seonna in my life as a dear friend. Love you Seonna-ya!!!

PS - the final pic in this carousel was a collab between  Seonna and I that benefitted  @compassioninsgv and @redcanarysong back in 2021

This painting, the title, the meaning behind it, couldn’t be more apropos for what New York City and many parts of the world are dealing with right now. Hope everyone is ok out there. 

Show Opens Saturday June 10, 6-8 pm. Hope to see you there. 💙

Tonight in NYC! My solo exhibition opens at @hashimotocontemporary!
⁠
Opening at 54 Ludlow Street from 6pm to 8pm. Hope to see you there!

“People Person” (diptych), 2023 
48 x 72”
Mixed Media on Canvas

Wow. All the jitters finally gave way to the warm wash of love and gratitude as I stepped into the gallery last Saturday. Thank you thank you thank you to all who came to the opening from near and far, for the messages of love from those who couldn’t, the most amazing surprises, the connections and re-connections. 

This new body of work is about that, reconnecting to humanity after the collective experience of what we’ve all gone through these last three years. In some ways, I’m re-learning how, some things are wonderfully familiar and some are forever changed. 

Thank you to @jennifersrizzo, @ken_harman_hashimoto and everyone at @hashimotocontemporary for having me and my work in your gorgeous new (to me) space for my 5th solo show with you and for supporting me as I figure things out about myself and my work. I love our origin story Ken, it really means so much to know.

The show runs through July 1. I really hope you get a chance to see it. Thank you! 💚

📸 @newwavetony

Thanks for the 💚 @juxtapozmag!

Q:What did one ghost say to the other? A:Do you believe in people?

I do. And kindness and love. Someone told me at my opening they also felt hope and that meant so much to me because that’s what I went into this body of work trying to reconnect to, even when it feels hard to.

Posted @withregram • @gilmancontemporary New Artist Alert:⁠
Introducing artist Seonna Hong⁠
We are thrilled to include her work in our annual #deckthewalls exhibition opening December 18th. ⁠
⁠
My work has always been about relational dynamics: friend to friend, love to love, mother to child... but in recent years it’s grown from the microcosm of my little world to include the relational dynamics of individual to community, community to the world at large and the world at large and the environment⁠
⁠
The work is in the gallery now or visit the link in bio to view more.
